Here’s a more intentional approach to error handling in a Node.js backend API:

js
app.get('/users', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const users = await db.getUsers();
    res.json(users);
  } catch (err) {
    logger.error(err); // Log the error for debugging
    res.status(500).json({ message: "Something went wrong" });
  }
};


This snippet ensures that errors are logged for debugging and a user-friendly response is sent, rather than exposing raw error details to the client.
